<h5>
Presentation 1: Animal Advocacy or Ethnocentrism: The
Interventionist’s Dilemma
</h5>

<p>
Author: Jodey Castricano<br>
Speaker: Jodey Castricano (University of British Columbia)
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
A recent posting on social media from a group called No Kill New York in
regards to animal slaughter states unequivocally, &quot;There is no right way to
kill someone who does not want to die.&quot; Indeed, in recent years the issue of
killing animals in agribusiness or for research has been filtering not only
into public consciousness but also into legislation and law. While the
“ethical turn” in Critical Animal Studies has arguably increased awareness
of the plight of animals in research, factory farming and entertainment it has
also encountered a fork in the road where tensions and alliances emerge
between animal and decolonial activisms. Bringing together the work of
Margaret Robinson on Mi’maq food practices and Magfirah Dahlan-Taylor
animals and food practices in Islam this paper takes a postcolonial, feminist
approach to navigating the dilemma facing CAS wherein Eurocentric
animal advocacy often demonizes non-Western human-animal relations as
uncivilized and barbaric.
</p>
