<h5>
Presentation 2: On the terms of the animal liberation: Beyond analogies
</h5>

<p>
Author: Zeynep Gizem Haspolat<br>

Speaker: Zeynep Gizem Haspolat (Rice University)
</p>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
In animal rights discourse, human slavery is often evoked as an analogy to
the conditions nonhuman animals are experiencing today. This analogy
emphasizes the arbitrary exclusion of certain beings from mattering and
their absolute inclusion into the productivity regimes as objects. Recent
social scientific analyses on race and animality, however, criticize this
analogy for its temporal and ethical assumptions. The analogy, it is argued,
perpetuates the subordinate existence of certain human groups and
nonhuman animals rather than turning the connections between these
systems of oppression into points of departure for defiance. This paper
dwells on the concept of the “unthinkable” developed by Bourdieu (1971;

1980; 1982) in order to question the limits of this analogy today. The paper
uses the unthinkable as a concept to speculate on the possibility of
enactments of the unthinkable, not necessarily only in a future to come, but
today, within the universe of the thinkables.
</p>
