<h5>Presentation 3: Does Valuing Animals Detract from Valuing Humans?
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Joshua Rottman, Charlie Crimston, &amp; Stylianos Syropoulos<br>
Speaker: Joshua Rottman (Franklin &amp; Marshall College) </p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Valuing animals and ecosystems is typically portrayed as an expansion of
moral concern. However, trade-offs exist in valuing different kinds of
entities, and moral valuation is often treated as zero-sum. Thus, valuing
animals and ecosystems may diminish value for humans. Across three
studies (N = 985), we found that a substantial number of people value
animals (e.g., dolphins) and habitats (e.g., rainforests) more than they
value humans from marginalized/stigmatized groups (e.g., Arabs,
Scientologists). This tendency was predicted by having relatively amplified
tendencies to attribute mental capacities to animals and relatively reduced
tendencies to attribute mental capacities to outgroup members. Our data
additionally demonstrated that morally prioritizing animals and nature was
not indicative of more expansive moral concern overall. Thus, animal
advocates should be mindful that morally valuing non-humans may detract
from morally valuing humanity. Future research should determine how to
encourage people to attribute moral worth in a non-zero-sum manner.
</p>
